{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"0655f9542fd5b43b7bfe796960233251","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The user wants to know what happens in cluster_consult when the factsheet is stale. I've already read the relevant files, so I can answer from memory of what I read.\n\nFrom `src/clusterConsult.ts`, the `consultCluster` function:\n\n1. It calls `loadClusterContext` which gets the cluster, factsheet, and file hashes\n2. It checks if `loaded.factsheet.status !== \"llm_verified\"` AND `loaded.cluster.static_factsheet_policy !== \"allow\"` — if so, returns error `CLUSTER_FACTSHEET_UNTRUSTED`\n3. It calls `findStaleFiles` to compare current file hashes against stored hashes\n\n\n4. When stale files are detected, it marks the factsheet as stale in the database and logs a cluster event before returning the `CLUSTER_FACTSHEET_STALE` error\n\nThen `tools.ts` has a fallback mechanism in `consultClusterForCaller` that handles how this error propagates to the caller.\n\nWhen `CLUSTER_FACTSHEET_STALE` is encountered, it first checks if `auto_refresh` is disabled—if so, it immediately falls back to `claude_consult`. But if auto-refresh is enabled, it attempts to revalidate the evidence by checking selectors and snippet hashes. If that revalidation fails, it marks the cluster as needing preparation and falls back to `claude_consult` anyway, with appropriate logging throughout.","signature":"7aa21ff0a99193eb0407be94376ecf7cfe68739de26aa236251c2aabdf43d2fa"}],"model":"MiniMax-M2.7","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":102420,"output_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0},"service_tier":"standard","context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"b299724c-1497-410c-96dd-2f782477c674","uuid":"3f7d5abb-9eff-44a6-bb64-23bbf81411fc"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"0655f9542fd5b43b7bfe796960233251","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"\n\nFrom `src/clusterConsult.ts:62-79`, the stale check happens immediately after loading context:\n\n```ts\nconst staleFiles = findStaleFiles(cwd, loaded.fileHashes);\nif (staleFiles.length > 0) {\n  db.markClusterFactsheetStale(loaded.factsheet.id);\n  db.logClusterEvent({\n    clusterId: input.clusterId,\n    projectId: input.projectId,\n    eventType: \"cluster_refresh_required\",\n    details: { factsheet_id: loaded.factsheet.id, factsheet_version: loaded.factsheet.version, changed_files: staleFiles }\n  });\n  return errorPayload(ERROR_CODES.CLUSTER_FACTSHEET_STALE, ..., { cluster_id: input.clusterId, details: { changed_files: staleFiles } });\n}\n```\n\nThis **returns the error upward**. The caller-facing behavior in `tools.ts:consultClusterForCaller` (lines 771–817) then decides what the caller sees:\n\n1. **Without `auto_refresh`:** immediately falls back to normal `claude_consult` (internal fallback, same question) — caller gets a normal answer, not an error.\n2. **With `auto_refresh`:** under a per-cluster lock, re-validates every cited `selector`/`snippet_hash`. If revalidation passes, the consult proceeds. If it fails, marks cluster `needs_prepare` and falls back to `claude_consult`.\n\nSo there are two distinct stale-paths: a **fast fallback** (no refresh) and a **strict revalidation path** (auto_refresh enabled). Neither path returns a stale error to the caller in the MVP — the caller always gets an answer."}],"model":"MiniMax-M2.7","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":102420,"output_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0},"service_tier":"standard","context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"b299724c-1497-410c-96dd-2f782477c674","uuid":"16b56be2-f738-4cc0-a344-4b7d0d840e01"}
